## MODEL ROUTING — WHICH MODEL FOR WHICH TASK

| Model | Budget Tier | Use For |
|---|---|---|
| `cursor-small` | 💚 Cheapest | Single-line completions, variable renaming only |
| `deepseek` | 💚 Cheapest | Simple lookups, reading files, explaining code — via OpenRouter |
| `cursor-composer` | 💛 Standard | **DEFAULT** — all agent tasks, slash commands, multi-file fixes, plan execution |
| `claude-sonnet` | 🟠 Premium | Complex reasoning with explanation, architectural discussion, code review |
| `claude-opus` | 🔴 Expensive | Architecture decisions, 5+ file cross-cutting refactors, security audits |
| `o3-mini` | 🟠 Premium | Complex TypeScript generics, algorithmic logic |

**BUDGET TIERS EXPLAINED**:
- 💚 Cheapest: Use freely — request-based billing, minimal cost
- 💛 Standard: Default for all real work — good cost/quality ratio
- 🟠 Premium: Use intentionally — higher cost, reserve for complex tasks
- 🔴 Expensive: Max Mode = token-based billing — one session can cost significantly

**RULE**: `cursor-composer` for 90% of tasks. Escalate deliberately, never by default.

**Escalate to Opus ONLY when**:
- Fix requires changing both auth AND payments simultaneously
- Refactoring a file imported by 10+ files
- Designing new database schema integrating with existing tables
- Running /security-audit (needs deep reasoning)

**⚠️ MAX MODE BILLING (March 2026)**: Claude Opus 4.6, Sonnet 4.6 now use token-based billing in Max Mode. Estimate before using: a 2K token prompt + 1K response = ~3K tokens. At scale this adds up fast. Use `cursor-composer` unless the task genuinely requires deeper reasoning.

